SIMPLE: mot
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mot
<hw>Mot</hw> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>Sing.
pres. ind.</pos> <conjf>Mot</conjf>, <conjf>Mote</conjf>,
<conjf>Moot</conjf> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>pl.</pos>
<conjf>Mot</conjf>, <conjf>Mote</conjf>, <conjf>Moote</conjf>,
<pos>pres. subj.</pos> <conjf>Mote</conjf>; <pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Moste</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Must</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <def>May; must;
might.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>moot</qex> as well say one word as another</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wordes <qex>mote</qex> be cousin to the deed.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men <qex>moot</qex> [i.e., one only] give silver to the poore
freres.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>So mote it be</b></col>, <cd>so be it; amen; -- a phrase
in some rituals, as that of the Freemasons.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mot
<hw>Mot</hw> <pr>(m⟦ocr⟧t; m⟦osl⟧, def. 2)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
See <er>Motto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A word; hence, a motto; a
device.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tarquin's eye may read the <qex>mot</qex> afar.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A pithy or witty saying; a witticism.</def> <mark>[A
Gallicism]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here and there turns up a . . . savage <qex>mot</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>N. Brit. Rev.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A note or brief strain on a bugle.</def> <rj><au>Sir
W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motacil</ent>⟦br⟧
